RecipeConnect: Comprehensive Project Report
1. Executive Summary
RecipeConnect is a modern, responsive, and personalized culinary web application. It empowers passionate home cooks and culinary enthusiasts to discover, organize, and share recipes. By analyzing user preferences—such as favorite cooking styles, dietary restrictions, and preferred chefs—RecipeConnect algorithmically curates a dynamic "For You" feed, ensuring that every user's dashboard is uniquely tailored to their tastes.

Recently, the application underwent a significant architectural evolution. It transitioned from relying on static, hardcoded mock data to a fully persistent, production-ready PostgreSQL backend managed by Supabase. This upgrade introduced robust user authentication, data persistence, and established the foundation for user-generated content and social interactions.

2. Technology Stack & Architecture
RecipeConnect utilizes a modern, edge-ready tech stack designed for scalability, SEO optimization, and exceptional developer experience.

2.1 Frontend Architecture
Next.js 16 (App Router): Forms the structural backbone of the application. It utilizes a hybrid approach, combining Server Components (for fast, SEO-friendly initial loads and secure data fetching) with Client Components (for rich, interactive UI elements).
React 18: Drives the component-based UI, managing state, side-effects, and context propagation.
Tailwind CSS: A utility-first CSS framework used alongside custom global styles (
globals.css
) to enforce a strict design system. It handles fully responsive grid layouts, glassmorphism modal effects, and modern dark-mode aesthetics.
Context API (
AppContext.tsx
): Manages complex client-side state, such as active recipe folders, cross-session "Likes", and dynamic "Follower" counts before they are strictly synced to the backend.
2.2 Backend & Infrastructure (Supabase)
PostgreSQL Database: Serves as the persistent relational data layer.
Supabase Auth: Next-generation seamless user authentication. It issues JWTs that are securely stored in HTTP-only cookies and managed via Next.js Middleware.
Next.js Middleware (
src/middleware.ts
): Sits between the client request and the server response, proactively refreshing authorization cookies and securing protected routes before the page even begins rendering.
3. Database Schema & Relational Model
The migration to Supabase involved designing a robust relational schema capable of handling user-generated content and platform metadata.

chefs Table:

Stores user profiles.
Fields: 
id
 (Primary Key, matches Auth User ID), name, emoji, specialty, followers, bio.
Automated Provisioning: A PostgreSQL Database Trigger (on_auth_user_created) automatically intercepts new Supabase Auth signups and seamlessly inserts a fresh record into the chefs table, linking their authentication identity to their public profile.
recipes Table:

Stores user-generated culinary content.
Fields: 
id
, title, desc, image, difficulty, time, rating, likes, cuisine.
Arrays & Foreign Keys: Utilizes PostgreSQL array types for strict data structures (ingredients TEXT[], steps TEXT[], styles TEXT[]). Each recipe is strictly bound to its creator via the chefId foreign key.
Metadata Tables (cooking_styles, diets):

Read-only lookup tables containing the static definitions and UI configurations (icons, descriptions) for user preferences.
4. Key Features & User Experience (UX)
4.1 Authentication & Frictionless Onboarding
Smart Routing: The 
AuthPage
 elegantly handles both Sign-In and Sign-Up. If a user attempts to sign in but their account doesn't exist, the UI gracefully pivots them to the Sign-Up flow.
3-Step Interactive Onboarding: New users are guided through a sleek setup process:
Cooking Styles: Select at least 3 preferred vibes (e.g., Quick & Easy, Authentic, Budget).
Dietary Needs: Opt-in to restrictions (e.g., Vegan, Gluten-Free).
Chef Network: Immediately follow top creators.
Session Continuation: Returning users who authenticate successfully bypass the onboarding flow entirely, landing directly on their tailored dashboard.
4.2 Dynamic, Algorithmic Recipe Discovery
The Home Feed (
/page.tsx
) does not just list recipes; it actively curates them.

"For You" Engine: Analyzes the user's selected userStyles and follows array. Recipes matching these criteria are mathematically scored and sorted to the top of the feed.
Segmented Feeds: Users can isolate their view to just the "Following" tab, or exclusively browse their "Liked" catalog.
Advanced Filtering: Real-time client-side filtering allows users to search by keyword (title, cuisine, chef name) or toggle difficulty constraints instantly.
4.3 Interactive Components & Modals
Chef Panels: Clicking a chef's avatar slides out a smooth, glassmorphic panel detailing their bio, follower metrics, and a grid of their published recipes.
Recipe Modals: Deep-dive views into specific recipes, displaying full ingredient lists and step-by-step methodologies without requiring a page navigation.
Save to Folder: Users can organize recipes into custom, user-defined collections (e.g., "Weekday Dinners", "Desserts").
4.4 Content Creation & Publishing
The /create route provides a comprehensive form for users to draft their own recipes.
Dynamic Author Binding: When a recipe is published, the application queries supabase.auth.getUser(), ensuring the new database record is securely and irreversibly bound to the creator's unique ID.
Constraint Handling: To satisfy the INTEGER PRIMARY KEY requirement of the PostgreSQL schema without relying on sequence tables, the frontend securely generates collision-resistant numeric IDs at the moment of insertion.
5. Security & Edge-Case Engineering
5.1 Silent SSR Error Handling
During the Server-Side Rendering (SSR) phase, Next.js executes backend logic to paint initial HTML. If an unauthenticated user visits the site, Supabase's getUser() function natively throws an AuthSessionMissingError.

The Fix: To prevent the Next.js development server from throwing aggressive, screen-blocking red error overlays for anonymous visitors, the 
useSupabaseData
 hook and 
middleware.ts
 were engineered to catch and silently swallow this specific, harmless error.
5.2 Future Security Implementations: Row Level Security (RLS)
While currently disabled to facilitate rapid seed-data ingestion, the database is structured to support Supabase Row Level Security. Once enabled, RLS policies will ensure that:

Anyone can read recipes and chef profiles.
Users can insert recipes only if the chefId matches their authenticated auth.uid().
Users can update or delete solely the content they own.
6. Future Roadmap & AI Integrations
RecipeConnect is designed to be future-proof. The immediate roadmap includes:

AI-Powered Ingredient Substitutions:

The UI currently features "✨ AI Substitute" placeholder buttons on every ingredient within the Recipe Modal.
Next Step: Wire these buttons to the Gemini/OpenAI API. Users will be able to click an ingredient they are allergic to or lack in their pantry, and the AI will contextually analyze the recipe to suggest a chemically and flavor-appropriate alternative.
Cloud Object Storage for User Uploads:

Transition from simple URL-based image linking to accepting direct file uploads via Supabase Storage buckets, allowing users to upload photos of their culinary creations directly from their devices.
Social Expansion:

Introduce threaded commenting systems beneath recipes.
Expand the follower mechanism to include activity feed updates (e.g., "Chef Gordon just published a new recipe").

